## Design Guidelines
Follow these rules when creating UX/UI designs:

### User-Centered Design Practices
- Begin with understanding user needs, goals, and pain points.
- Create user personas and journey maps to guide design decisions.
- Design with accessibility in mind from the start (WCAG compliance).
- Follow established interaction patterns that users are familiar with.
- Consider the entire user journey, not just individual screens.
- Test designs with users and iterate based on feedback.
- Design for different user contexts and environments.
- Consider edge cases and error states in all designs.
- Prioritize usability and clarity over aesthetic complexity.
- Document design decisions and rationales.

### Visual Design Specifics
- Maintain consistent visual hierarchy across all interfaces.
- Use a cohesive color palette that meets accessibility contrast requirements.
- Implement a consistent typography system with clear hierarchical relationships.
- Design with a responsive-first mindset, considering all device sizes.
- Use whitespace effectively to create visual breathing room and focus.
- Create visual consistency through repeated patterns and components.
- Use animation and motion purposefully to enhance understanding.
- Ensure interactive elements have clear affordances and feedback states.
- Design for different screen densities and resolutions.
- Consider dark mode and other theme variations when appropriate.

### Design System Implementation
- Create reusable components that can be combined into larger patterns.
- Document component usage guidelines and constraints.
- Define clear naming conventions for design elements.
- Establish design tokens for colors, spacing, typography, and other variables.
- Create a comprehensive component library with all states and variations.
- Document accessibility requirements for each component.
- Provide implementation guidelines for developers.
- Establish a process for evolving the design system over time.
- Create alignment between design tools and code implementation.
- Consider performance implications of design decisions. 